---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<Layout 
  title="Cannabis Taxation & 280E | Maine Dispensary Guide" 
  description="Understanding cannabis business taxation in Maine including IRC Section 280E, state taxes, and compliance requirements."
  heroImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1554224155-6726b3ff858f?auto=format&fit=crop&q=80&w=1200&h=400"
>
  <article>
    <div class="article-header">
      <h1>Cannabis Taxation & 280E</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Understanding cannabis business <a href="/guides/maine-cannabis-taxation-280e/">taxation</a> in Maine</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p>Cannabis businesses face unique tax challenges due to federal prohibition. IRC Section <a href="/glossary/#280e-(internal-revenue-code)">280E</a> prohibits cannabis businesses from taking normal business deductions, resulting in significantly higher effective tax rates. Understanding these requirements is critical for financial planning.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="Navigating the Complexity" type="tip">
      While the tax landscape for cannabis might seem daunting, mastering it is a powerful way to professionalize your business. With the right strategies and a solid accounting partner, you can turn these challenges into a competitive advantage by operating a lean, efficient, and highly compliant dispensary.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Section 280E Explained</h2>
      <p>Section <a href="/glossary/#280e-(internal-revenue-code)">280E</a> was originally enacted to prevent drug traffickers from deducting business expenses. Because cannabis remains illegal at the federal level, cannabis businesses are subject to this provision.</p>
      
      <h3>What It Means:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You cannot deduct ordinary business expenses</li>
        <li>Only Cost of Goods Sold (COGS) is deductible</li>
        <li>Effective tax rate can be 70-90%+ of profits</li>
        <li>Applies to all cannabis businesses regardless of state legality</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)</h2>
      <p>While deductions are limited, you can still reduce taxable income through COGS:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Direct product costs</li>
        <li>Inventory costs</li>
        <li>Direct labor (production)</li>
        <li>Manufacturing overhead</li>
        <li>Shipping and handling (product-related)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Maine State Taxes</h2>
      <p>In addition to federal taxes, Maine imposes:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Maine Corporate Income Tax</strong> - 8.93% for C-Corps</li>
        <li><strong>Sales Tax</strong> - Cannabis sales subject to Maine sales tax</li>
        <li><strong>Local Taxes</strong> - Some municipalities may impose additional taxes</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Tax Planning Strategies</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Structure as C-Corp</strong> - May provide some benefits</li>
        <li><strong>Maximize COGS</strong> - Document all product-related costs</li>
        <li><strong>Qualified Business Income</strong> - Potential 20% deduction</li>
        <li><strong>Employee Benefits</strong> - Some may be deductible</li>
        <li><strong>State Tax Credits</strong> - Research Maine-specific credits</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Compliance Requirements</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Maintain detailed financial records</li>
        <li>Separate business and personal expenses</li>
        <li>Work with cannabis-experienced accountants</li>
        <li>Quarterly estimated tax payments</li>
        <li>Properly classify employees vs. contractors</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Section 280E significantly limits deductions</li>
        <li>Work with cannabis tax specialists</li>
        <li>Plan for 70%+ effective tax rate</li>
        <li>Maximize COGS deductions</li>
        <li>Quarterly estimated payments required</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="further-reading">
      <h2>Further Reading</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.maine.gov/dafs/ocp/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Maine Office of Cannabis Policy (OCP)</a></li>
        <li><a href="https://www.maine.gov/revenue/taxes/corporate-income-tax" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Maine Revenue Services - Corporate Income Tax</a></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="disclaimer">
      <p><em>This is for informational purposes only. Consult a qualified cannabis tax professional for specific advice.</em></p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  article { max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 2rem; padding-bottom: 1.5rem; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  .subtitle { font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--color-text-light); }
  section { margin-bottom: 2rem; }
  section h2, section h3 { margin-top: 1.5rem; }
  section h2:first-child { margin-top: 0; }
  table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1rem 0; }
  th, td { padding: 0.75rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border); }
  th { background: var(--color-background); }
  ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; }
  li { margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
  .disclaimer { background: #fff3cd; border: 1px solid #ffc107; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 0.5rem; font-size: 0.875rem; }
  .further-reading { background: rgba(88, 129, 87, 0.05); padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 1rem; margin-top: 3rem; }
  .further-reading h2 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.25rem; }
</style>
